* User Help Guide – How to Upload Files on GitHub* 

1. Upload Files Through GitHub Website (Easiest)

Step 1 — Open Your Repository
Go to: https://github.com/Shreya21Mahajan/Skin-Disease-Prediction-Model

Step 2 — Click "Add file"

Step 3 — Select "Upload files"

Step 4 — Drag and Drop Your Files
Examples: .py, .html, .css, .pptx, .docx, .pdf, .jpg, .png

Step 5 — Commit Changes
Scroll down and click "Commit changes".

2. Upload Files Using Git (Advanced)

Step 1 — Place your file inside your project folder.

Step 2 — Open Terminal.

Step 3 — Run:
git add yourfile.ext

Step 4 — Commit:
git commit -m "Added new file"

Step 5 — Push:
git push

3. Upload Files Inside a Folder (Recommended)

Create folders like:
docs/  (PPT, reports)
models/ (ML models)
templates/ (HTML)
src/ (ML scripts)

To upload:
Open folder → Add file → Upload files → Commit.

Important Notes
- GitHub upload limit: 100 MB/file
- Do NOT upload environment folders (env/, venv/, tfenv/)
- Do NOT upload large datasets
- Do NOT upload passwords or secret keys

Tips
- Use GitHub Desktop if you're a beginner.
- Keep file names simple and clean.
- Use docs/ folder for PPT and Word files.

You’re Ready!
You can now upload any file to GitHub safely.

